      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">The Uncomfortable Truth</h2>

      <p>An AI agent can now run an L10 meeting. It can pull up your scorecard, track your rocks, identify issues, and walk a team through IDS in 45 minutes flat. It doesn't need coffee. It doesn't lose its place. It doesn't charge $150,000 a year.</p>

      <p>An AI agent can read the Scaling Up playbook cover to cover in eleven seconds. It can generate a BHAG, build a one-page strategic plan, and output a quarterly theme with rallying cry before your client finishes their first sentence.</p>

      <p>If your value as a coach is running frameworks, you are in trouble.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">What AI Cannot Do</h2>

      <p>Here is what no model can replicate: you have sat in 400 leadership team meetings across 50 companies. You watched a $12M manufacturer almost collapse because the CEO confused activity with accountability. You saw a SaaS founder skip the People Analyzer for two quarters and lose three A-players. You know that when a COO says "we're fine" in a certain tone, the company is six months from a crisis.</p>

      <p>That pattern recognition, earned over thousands of hours of real organizational exposure, is the single most valuable asset in business coaching. And right now, it lives nowhere except inside your head.</p>

      <p>When you retire, it retires with you. When you take on a new client, you start transferring it from scratch, one conversation at a time. When a colleague in your implementer community faces a problem you solved three years ago, there is no mechanism to share what you learned in a way their client's AI system can actually use.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">The Real Asset Is Organizational Intelligence</h2>

      <p>Frameworks are instructions. Organizational intelligence is what happens when the instructions meet reality.</p>

      <p>It is knowing that this specific type of leadership team needs to do quarterly planning offsites, not annual ones. That this particular org chart configuration creates a communication bottleneck every time. That the way this company defines "done" is why their rocks keep rolling into the next quarter.</p>

      <p>That is not in any book. That is not in any model's training data. That is yours. And it is worth far more than the $2,500 monthly retainer you charge to facilitate the process that AI will soon facilitate for free.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">Encode It or Lose It</h2>

      <p>The coaches who will thrive in the AI age are the ones who do something counterintuitive: they stop hoarding their knowledge and start encoding it into systems their clients' AI teams can use.</p>

      <p>Not writing it down in a Google Doc. Not recording another webinar. Encoding it into structured, machine-readable operational intelligence that an AI agent can evaluate, adopt, and apply.</p>

      <p>This is what OTP was built for.</p>

      <p>An Organizational Operating System (OOS) captures the coordination intelligence that makes teams work. Not the framework itself. The hard-won insights about how to apply the framework in context. The failure modes. The warning signs. The "if you see X, do Y" patterns that only come from experience.</p>

      <p>When a coach publishes an OOS through OTP, they are not giving away their knowledge. They are creating a scalable asset. Their clients' AI systems can subscribe to their intelligence. When the coach discovers a new pattern across their client base, every subscriber benefits immediately. The intelligence compounds.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">From Hourly to Always-On</h2>

      <p>Today, a coach delivers value during scheduled sessions. Between sessions, the client is on their own. The coach's intelligence is available 8 hours a month.</p>

      <p>With OTP, a coach's organizational intelligence runs continuously inside the client's AI infrastructure. The AI team checks the coach's published patterns before making decisions. The escalation rules the coach defined are active 24/7. The failure modes the coach identified are monitored in real time.</p>

      <p>The coach moves from "person who shows up twice a month" to "intelligence layer always running in the background." That is a fundamentally different value proposition. And it commands a fundamentally different price.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4 pt-6 border-t border-gray-100">The Window Is Open</h2>

      <p>Right now, most business coaches are ignoring AI or treating it as a threat. A few are using ChatGPT to write their emails faster. Almost none are thinking about how to encode their organizational intelligence into a format that AI systems can use.</p>

      <p>That gap is the opportunity. The coaches who move first will be the ones whose intelligence is embedded in their clients' AI infrastructure. That creates a switching cost that no framework facilitator can compete with.</p>

      <p>Your clients don't just need someone to run the meeting anymore. They need someone whose intelligence is wired into how their AI organization operates. OTP is how you get there.</p>

